lead_paragraph: The California Supreme Court unanimously refused today to lift a Sacramento judge's order forbidding The Wall Street Journal from calling its weekly California-focused pages ''California Journal,'' the same name as a political magazine. The Wall Street Journal, with a circulation of 1.8 million, including 280,000 in California, said last month it would publish five pages of regional financial news each Wednesday under the name California Journal. It publishes the Texas Journal, the Florida Journal and the Southeast Journal as regional sections.
abstract: California Supreme Court unanimously refuses to lift Sacramento judge's order forbidding Wall Street Journal from calling its weekly California-focused pages California Journal, same name as political magazine (S)

headline.main: Wall Street Journal Loses Battle Over Name
